Upon the earth, a shadow fell, the crowd uncertain, tense, and awed—
On the scene came Christ The Lord, not with peace but with a sword.
He spoke in thunder, not in whispers, cleaving silence, breaking norms;
He summoned storms inside the heart, and called the restless to transform.
Not comfort, but a challenge, He set before the weary crowd;
Dividing love from merely habit, truth from what we say aloud.
His blade was not of steel or stone, but sharper—words that burn and sear;
Inviting all to risk and follow, though the path was paved with fear.
For sometimes peace is born from strife, and justice from a sacred fight;
So Christ arrived to stir the world, and draw us nearer to the light.

On the scene came Christ The Lord, not with peace but with a sword,
A blade of vision, sharp and bright, to cut through shadows of the night.
He cleft the silence, roused the meek, called the lost and raised the weak;
Not to soothe the world to sleep, but to rouse the depths of souls so deep.
His sword was truth, unwavering, cleaving lies and suffering;
He did not bring a gentle rest, but trials to reveal the best.
Dividing kin and friend and foe, so each might find the way to grow;
He beckoned us to rise, to see, the cost of love and liberty.
So let the sword of Christ descend, to break, to heal, and to defend.
